## Related

* Closes https://github.com/rerun-io/rerun/issues/9581

## What

This is a full rewrite of the callback API.

The callback interface has been unified into a single `on_event` callback. This results in the removal of many layers of boilerplate, but a few still remain:

* `ViewerEvent` definition in Rust in `crates/viewer/re_viewer/event.rs`.
  * This definition uses a few custom serialization/deserialization methods through `serde(with = "...")`, for example to serialize `EventPath` as a string instead of an array of strings. This makes the downstream APIs a lot nicer. All the custom serialization is defined in the same file.
* `ViewerEvent` definition in the Web Viewer API in `rerun_js/web-viewer/index.ts`.
  * Because the Viewer outputs events as JSON, they can be deserialized into JavaScript objects without any extra boilerplate, via `JSON.parse`
* `ViewerEvent` definition in the Python SDK in `rerun_py/rerun_sdk/rerun/event.py`
  * Deserialization is done manually.

I hope there is some way to get rid of the need to manually update type definitions and the Python deserialization code, but I'm leaving that for a future follow-up:

* https://github.com/rerun-io/rerun/issues/9740

I've had to update the remaining layers many times while writing this PR, and I can confirm that overall, it is a huge improvement. Instead of having to remember all the different layers, you only have to grep for `ViewerEvent`. 

### Rust API changes

The Rust API now exposes `on_event` in `StartupOptions`, and `callbacks` has been removed. `on_event` yields instances of `ViewerEvent`. The `ViewerEvent` definition includes shared fields, such as `recording_id`.

Users can `match` on the specific event kind in the callback:

```rust
let startup_options = re_viewer::StartupOptions {
    on_event: Arc::new(move |event: re_viewer::ViewerEvent| {
        event.recording_id;
        match event.kind {
            re_viewer::ViewerEventKind::SelectionChange(selection) => {
                for item in selection.items {
                    // ...
                }
            }
            _ => {}
        }
    });
};
```

### Web Viewer API changes

The Web Viewer API exposes events in the same way as before, using the `EventEmitter` pattern. The events have been renamed to `snake_case`:

* `timeupdate` to `time_update`
* `timelinechange` to `timeline_change`
* `selectionchange` to `selection_change`

The callback now yields subtypes of `ViewerEvent`. Each subtype of `ViewerEvent` inherits from `ViewerEventBase`, which defines shared fields, such as `recording_id`. Concrete event types define the payload inline.

```ts
viewer.on("selection_change", event => console.log(event.recording_id, event.items));
```

### Jupyter Notebook API changes

The `Viewer` class now has an `on_event` method, and `register_callbacks` has been removed. The `on_event` method accepts a single callback instead of a class. The callback is called with instances of `ViewerEvent`.

Just like TS, we expose some shared fields on `ViewerEvent` (by inheriting from a `ViewerEventBase` class), and event-specific payloads are placed inline.

Each event class comes with a `type` property, which may be used to discriminate the event. This form of type discrimination is something which Python type checkers and language servers understand, so it results in type narrowing inside `if/elif/else` and `match`.

```python
def on_viewer_event(event: ViewerEvent):
  if event.type == "selection_change":
    # note: `event` has type `SelectionChangeEvent`
    for item in event.items:
      pass # do something with `item`

viewer.on_event(on_viewer_event)
```
